    <text>
        <body>
            <head>6. Telegram From the Embassy in <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW"
                    >Egypt</placeName> to the Department of State<note n="1" place="foot"
                    type="source" xml:id="d6fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign
                    Policy File, D770133–0249. Secret; Priority; <gloss target="#t_Exdis_1"
                        >Exdis</gloss>. Sent for information to Tripoli.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Cairo</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1977-04-16T12:45:00+00:00">April 16, 1977, 1245Z</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>6378. Subj: <persName corresp="recepwADCEWxlTqkQ">Fahmy</persName> on <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>. Ref: Cairo 6369.<note n="2"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d6fn2">Telegram 6369 from Cairo, April 16, is in the
                    National Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File, D770133–0257.</note>
            </p>
            <p>1. When meeting with <persName corresp="recepwADCEWxlTqkQ">Fahmy</persName> today, I
                alluded to current <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="rec80ZRVkTQfLW60o"
                    >Egyptian-Libyan</rs> strains and asked for his latest assessment of <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> situation.</p>
            <p>2. <persName corresp="recepwADCEWxlTqkQ">Fahmy</persName> claimed Egyptian burning of
                    <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> Relations Office in
                Alexandria was in direct retaliation for <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libyan</placeName> action against Egyptian Public Relations Office in Benghazi.
                He also acknowledged that <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName>
                diplomatic officials had been forbidden to leave <placeName
                    corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> until Egyptian officials in
                    <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> were allowed to leave.
                Judging from latest information available to <gloss target="#t_MFA_1">MFA</gloss>,
                Libyans are now allowing Egyptian officials to leave. However, relations between
                    <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> and <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> are tense and likely to remain so.
                Border, while not formally closed, is tightly controlled.</p>
            <p>2. <gloss target="#t_GOE_1">
                    <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">
                        <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">GOE</placeName>
                    </placeName>
                </gloss>, <persName corresp="recepwADCEWxlTqkQ">Fahmy</persName> emphasized, has no
                intention of involving the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United
                    States</placeName> in the Egyptian-<placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">
                    <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Lib</placeName>yan</placeName> dispute.
                    <gloss target="#t_GOE_1">
                    <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">GOE</placeName>
                </gloss> will take care of <pb facs="0034" n="13" xml:id="pg_13"/>
                <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> by itself. It is determined
                to get rid of <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">
                    <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Qad</placeName>hafi</persName> and is
                moving to achieve this. Decision has been made to topple him “in best interests of
                everyone.” <gloss target="#t_GOE_1">
                    <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">GOE</placeName>
                </gloss> will try to get rid of him in any way it can. Whether it is able to do so
                or not, <persName corresp="recepwADCEWxlTqkQ">Fahmy</persName> observed, remains to
                be seen.</p>
            <p>3. Noting Cairo press reports that <gloss target="#t_GOE_1">
                    <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">
                        <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">GOE</placeName>
                    </placeName>
                </gloss> is submitting a letter to the <orgName corresp="recNYDvUSAmpswfyd">
                    <orgName corresp="recNYDvUSAmpswfyd">Arab League</orgName>
                </orgName> about <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName>, <persName
                    corresp="recepwADCEWxlTqkQ">Fahmy</persName> stated that he had included in that
                letter a statement charging <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName>
                with plotting terrorist activities against “certain Embassies in some Arab
                countries” and that <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> will at
                the appropriate time provide details. In this connection, <persName
                    corresp="recepwADCEWxlTqkQ">Fahmy</persName> stated that he may at some time
                leak the <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> threat against
                    me.<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d6fn3">See <ref target="#d86">Document
                        86</ref>.</note>
            </p>
            <p>4. I noted that there continues to be sensitivity in Washington about disclosure and
                urged that he not do so without first consulting <gloss target="#t_US_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">
                        <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                    </placeName>
                </gloss>. <persName corresp="recepwADCEWxlTqkQ">Fahmy</persName> responded that
                Egyptian security officials have now obtained the whole story from the original
                source. He reiterated his frequently expressed concern that <gloss target="#t_USG_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">USG</rs>
                </gloss> is “soft” on <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> and
                seems to be trying to protect him. I told him that, as he should know from talks in
                Washington, the <gloss target="#t_USG_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">USG</rs>
                </gloss> is fully alive to the danger <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU"
                    >Qadhafi</persName> represents and is in no way seeking to protect him. As he
                also knew, we have been skeptical of <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU"
                    >Qadhafi</persName>’s overtures and have thus far refused <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>’s suggestions to exchange
                Ambassadors, release <rs type="topic" corresp="rec1GiKVfLPrlIGzK">C–130</rs>’s and
                take various other measures which <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libya</placeName> wants. Our Egyptian friends must recognize, however, that we
                must handle our <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recRtTKQqtxKMBMhV">
                    <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recRtTKQqtxKMBMhV">relations</rs>
                </rs> with <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">Li</placeName>bya in a manner
                which we consider will best serve <gloss target="#t_US_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                </gloss> interests.</p>
            <p>5. Comment: I fear some of our recent actions vis-a-vis <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>, including the demarche I was
                instructed to make just before <persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip"
                    >Sadat</persName>’s departure for the <gloss target="#t_US_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">
                        <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                    </placeName>
                </gloss>,<note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d6fn4">In telegram 5161 from Cairo, March
                    27, <persName corresp="rec7JYqcxT5FHBLcK">Eilts</persName> reported on his
                    meeting with <persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName>, during
                    which <persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName> declared his
                    intention to discuss with <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8"
                        >Carter</persName>
                    <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>’s “subversive”
                    activities in the <placeName corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle East</placeName>
                    and <placeName corresp="rech4Y08vWrfyBSYC">Africa</placeName>. (National
                    Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File, P850052–2156, N770002–0201)</note>
                our unwillingness publicly to disclose the <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libyan</placeName> threat against me, has persuaded senior <gloss
                    target="#t_GOE_1">
                    <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">
                        <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">GOE</placeName>
                    </placeName>
                </gloss> officials to believe that, regardless of what we say, we are in fact
                seeking to protect <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName>. Our
                protestations to the contrary are greeted with skepticism and even <persName
                    corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName>’s talks in Washington have not
                allayed that concern.<note n="5" place="foot" xml:id="d6fn5">
                    <persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName> was in Washington April
                    3–6. For the memoranda for conversation of his meetings, see <ref
                        target="frus1977-80v08#d25">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations,</hi> 1977–1980, vol. VIII,
                        Arab-Israeli Dispute, January 1977–August 1978, Documents 25</ref>–<ref
                        target="frus1977-80v08#d27">27</ref>.</note> We should not be surprised at
                this, since Egyptians are by nature suspicious and prone to read into things
                implications which are in no way intended. So long as this impression persists,
                however, we may find the Egyptians <pb facs="0035" n="14" xml:id="pg_14"/> somewhat
                more closemouthed in telling us about their plans vis-a-vis <persName
                    corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> and <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="rec7JYqcxT5FHBLcK">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Eilts</hi>
                    </persName>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
